  "text": "Kafka's log retention policy enforcement is distributed across multiple Java and Scala files in the storage and server-common modules. The core retention enforcement mechanism operates as follows:\n\n**Configuration and Validation (LogConfig.java, ServerLogConfigs.java, TopicConfig.java)**\nThe log retention policy is defined through configuration properties:\n- `retention.ms` (RETENTION_MS_CONFIG) in TopicConfig.java defines time-based retention\n- `retention.bytes` (RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG) in TopicConfig.java defines size-based retention\n- `local.retention.ms` and `local.retention.bytes` provide local-only retention for tiered storage\n\nValidation occurs in LogConfig.java through methods like validateBrokerLogConfigValues(), validateRemoteStorageRetentionTime(), and validateRemoteStorageRetentionSize() which ensure retention values are consistent and valid.\n\n**Retention Enforcement in UnifiedLog.java**\nThe UnifiedLog.java class (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/UnifiedLog.java) implements the actual retention cleanup mechanism:\n\n1. deleteOldSegments() (line 1894) - orchestrates the retention cleanup process by calling three deletion strategies\n2. deleteRetentionMsBreachedSegments() (line 1908) - implements time-based retention using the localRetentionMs() method (line 2646), which checks if segments have exceeded the retention time by comparing current time with segment's largest timestamp\n3. deleteRetentionSizeBreachedSegments() (line 1946) - implements size-based retention using localRetentionSize() (line 2650), which enforces that total log size doesn't exceed retentionBytes\n4. deleteLogStartOffsetBreachedSegments() (line 1977) - cleans up segments based on log start offset position\n5. deleteSegments() (line 1856) - actually performs the physical deletion of segments from disk\n\nThe localRetentionMs() and localRetentionSize() static methods (lines 2646-2651) return either the local retention values (for tiered storage) or the standard retention values, enabling support for both local-only and tiered storage scenarios.\n\n**Tiered Storage Retention in RemoteLogManager.java**\nFor tiered storage, RemoteLogManager.java (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/server/log/remote/storage/RemoteLogManager.java) implements parallel retention logic:\n- RemoteLogRetentionHandler inner class (line 1118) manages remote segment retention\n- buildRetentionTimeData() (line 1399) calculates the cleanup cutoff time based on retentionMs\n- buildRetentionSizeData() (line 1406) calculates the breached size for size-based retention\n- RetentionSizeData and RetentionTimeData inner classes store retention parameters\n\n**LogManager Coordination (LogManager.scala)**\nThe Scala-based LogManager in core/src/main/scala/kafka/log/LogManager.scala coordinates the retention check mechanism with a background thread that runs periodically (controlled by retentionCheckMs config in ServerLogConfigs.java at line 68-70).\n\nThe retention enforcement chain flows from configuration validation in LogConfig -> to metric calculation in LogManager -> to actual deletion execution in UnifiedLog.deleteOldSegments() which calls the specific retention breach detection methods (deleteRetentionMsBreachedSegments and deleteRetentionSizeBreachedSegments) and finally executes deleteSegments() to remove the segments from disk.\n"
}

